library('astsa')
data = read.csv("mortgage.txt", sep="")
morg = ts(data[4] ,frequency = 12, start = c(1971, 4), end = c(2011, 11)) 
ffr = ts(data[5] ,frequency = 12, start = c(1971, 4), end = c(2011, 11)) 
data_ts = ts.intersect(morg, ffr)

(a) Explain the data, why it is a time series data.

  1. Use exploratory analysis techniques to describe the data.
  2. Determine if the monthly mortgage rate series is stationary. If the series was not stationary apply appropriate transformation(s) to make the transformed series stationary.

This dataset is time series data because the observations are continuous data points sampled over time in even intervals which leads to the presence of dependance between the points.
The dataframe contains 5 columns: year, month, day, morg and ffr. Morg contains the monthly mortgage rates from April 1971 to November 2011 while ffr contains the monthly federal funds rates for the same time interval. Fig 1 shows both numeric variables visualized alongside. We can see the similalities in magnitude and trend. The time series is not stationary. If we want to fit a model to this data some transformation is in order which removes the trend, stebalizes the variance and the mean. Fig 2 desplays the linear relationship of morg and ffr which will aide in the construction of an accurate model. I fig 3 we look at the theoretical quantiles of each of these columns and notice a left-skewed distribution in both of them.

(d) Compute sample autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation functions for the monthly mortgage rate and explain their meanings. Is there any model suggested by the autocorrelation or partial autocorrelation functions?

The transformation that most effectivly provides stationarity to the time series is growth rate which we calculate by log(x_t) - log(x_t-1). Fig 5 shows what the time series looks like after such transformation along with their theoretcal quantiles. We can also see that morg has a more stebalized variance and their distribution looks less skewed. We now look at the acf and pacf of morg in fig 6. From the plots in fig 6 we can identify the stationarity is precent and there are a few models that could fit this data well. Some of the models to consider are MA(1) based on the significant lag 1, AR(2) based on the two significant lags 1 and 2, and ARIMA(2,0,1).

new_morg = log(morg) - log(lag(morg, -1))
new_ffr = log(ffr) - log(lag(ffr, -1))

layout(matrix(1:4,2), widths = c(2.5,1))

tsplot(new_morg, main = "Mortgage Rate", ylab = "",col = 4, margin = 0)
tsplot(new_ffr, main = "Federal Funds Rate", ylab = "",col = 4, margin = 0)

qqnorm(new_morg, main = "", col = 4) 
qqline(new_morg, col = 2, lwd = 2)
qqnorm(new_ffr, main = "", col = 4) 
qqline(new_ffr, col = 2, lwd = 2)

After observing the 3 suspected models and obtaining competitive results it was determined that the AR(2) is the best model containing the lowest AIC and AICc value.As we can see below the information criteria for each of the models:

Fig 7 shows some diagnostics for this model. From the residuals plot we can say it is reasonable to say they look like white noise with no identifiable trends or patterns. The QQ plot shows some outliers but otherwise follows the normal distribution reasonably well. The ACF shows no significant lags which indicates the residuals are independent. Finally all p-values for Ljung-Box statistic (Q-statistic) are over the threshhold and therefore no significant.

After observing the 3 suspected models and obtaining competitive results it was determined that the AR(2) is the best model containing the lowest AIC and AICc value. As we can see below the information criteria for each of the models:

Fig 9? shows some diagnostics for this model. From the residuals plot we can say it is reasonable to say they look like white noise with no identifiable trends or patterns. The QQ plot shows some outliers but otherwise follows the normal distribution reasonably well. The ACF shows no significant lags which indicates the residuals are identically and independent distributed. Finally all p-values for Ljung-Box statistic (Q-statistic) are well over the threshhold and therefore not significant.

reg1_values = c(reg1$AIC, reg1$AICc, reg1$BIC)
reg2_values = c(reg2$AIC, reg2$AICc, reg2$BIC)
reg3_values = c(reg3$AIC, reg3$AICc, reg3$BIC)
data.frame(reg1_values, reg2_values, reg3_values)
##   reg1_values reg2_values reg3_values

## 3   -4.372112   -4.386257   -4.383635

Thus the model we build is AR(2) with estimates as follows \[M_t\ =\ (-7\times 10^{-4})\ +\ (0.3921)\ F_{t-1}\ +\ (-0.2261)\ F_{t-2}\ +\ (0.0738)\ log(F_{t-1})\ +\ W_{t}\]
